\section{Conclusions and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
In this work, we presented Diffusion-Assisted Latent Wasserstein GAN (DALWGAN), a framework that integrates diffusion-based latent purification with adaptive latent space learning to address the challenges of modeling data on low-dimensional manifolds. By refining latent codes through a controlled diffusion process and enforcing latent consistency via a rank penalty, DALWGAN achieves robust generative modeling and accurate intrinsic dimension estimation. Experimental evaluations on both synthetic and real-world datasets demonstrate superior latent space alignment and enhanced sample fidelity compared to baseline models. Future work will explore stochastic variations of the encoder and generator, integration with high-capacity architectures for high-resolution image synthesis, and applications in diverse domains such as economic structural estimation, promising further improvements in the robustness and accuracy of generative models.

